      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        GST on real estate agent commission in Brisbane: how it affects net proceeds calculations
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Agent commissions are sometimes quoted excluding GST. Sellers who calculate net proceeds with the lower number receive an unwelcome surprise at settlement. Here is how GST on commission actually works.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most common surprises in a Brisbane property settlement is the size of the agent commission once GST is added. Sellers who model their net proceeds against a headline commission rate, then assume that figure is what hits the bank account, regularly find themselves several thousand dollars short. The cause is almost always the same: the commission was quoted exclusive of GST, and the seller calculated as if it were inclusive.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how GST is applied to agent services, how it affects the net proceeds calculation, what the settlement statement actually shows, and how to compare quotes on a like-for-like basis.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The basic rule</h2>
      <p>GST applies at 10% to real estate agent services in Australia. If the agent is registered for GST (and they almost always are; the threshold is well below typical agent turnover), the commission is grossed up by 10% before it is paid from settlement proceeds. This is not optional, and it is not negotiable.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">An example calculation</h2>
      <p>For a $1,000,000 sale at a 2.2% commission rate:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Agent commission (excluding GST): $22,000</li>
        <li>GST on commission: $2,200</li>
        <li>Total commission charged at settlement: $24,200</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The same calculation at scale: a $2,000,000 sale at the same rate adds $4,400 in GST on top of $44,000 in headline commission. For a vendor budgeting net proceeds, the difference between $44,000 and $48,400 is meaningful.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the agent's quote should show</h2>
      <p>A clear agent quote separates three things and labels each explicitly:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>The commission rate or amount, with a clear statement of whether the figure is GST-inclusive or GST-exclusive</li>
        <li>The estimated dollar value of the commission at the expected sale price</li>
        <li>The GST treatment of any vendor-paid advertising (advertising costs are also subject to GST)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you cannot tell from the quote whether GST is included, ask before signing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">GST on vendor-paid advertising</h2>
      <p>Advertising costs (portal listings, photography, video, signage, and print) are passed through the agent's trust account. Each component is subject to GST at the supplier level, and the agent passes that GST through as part of the trust account reconciliation. If you have agreed to a $5,000 vendor-paid marketing package, the actual amount drawn from settlement is $5,500 once GST is added. Confirm whether the marketing quote is presented inclusive or exclusive of GST in the same way you would for the commission.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The input tax credit angle</h2>
      <p>An individual seller selling their family home is not registered for GST and cannot claim input tax credits on agent commission. The GST is a real cost. For investor sellers running a property as part of a GST-registered business, the position is different and depends on the specific tax circumstances. Always check with a tax advisor before assuming GST on commission can be recovered. For most owner-occupiers and most individual investors holding property in their personal name, the GST is not recoverable and should be modelled as a cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Comparing agent quotes on a like-for-like basis</h2>
      <p>When you have two or three agent quotes in front of you, the only useful comparison is one where every figure is presented on the same basis. Pick GST-inclusive or GST-exclusive, then ask each agent to restate their quote that way. Calculate the total cost (commission plus advertising plus any other fees) for the expected sale price, and compare those final dollar numbers. Small differences in the headline commission rate can be magnified or reduced significantly by GST treatment and by the inclusion or exclusion of marketing.</p>
      <p>Two agents who appear to be quoting the same rate may be quoting very different total costs once GST and marketing are added. Two agents who appear to be quoting very different rates may end up at almost the same total cost once everything is on the same basis.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The trust account flow at settlement</h2>
      <p>When settlement happens, the buyer's funds flow through two trust accounts:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>The deposit (typically 5% to 10% of the sale price) sits in the agent's trust account from the contract date through to settlement</li>
        <li>The balance flows through the seller's solicitor's trust account at settlement</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The agent's commission (including GST) and any vendor-paid advertising (including GST) are paid from the agent's trust account before any deposit balance is returned to the seller. The seller receives the net proceeds (sale price minus all deductions) at or shortly after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the settlement statement shows</h2>
      <p>The settlement statement (sometimes called the trust account statement or settlement summary) is the single document that reconciles everything. A clear statement shows:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>The sale price</li>
        <li>The agent's commission as a separate line item</li>
        <li>GST on commission as a separate line</li>
        <li>Each vendor-paid advertising item, with GST shown separately</li>
        <li>The mortgage payout amount</li>
        <li>Any other contractual deductions (council rates, water rates, body corporate adjustments)</li>
        <li>The trust balance refund (or top-up) as the final adjustment</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Always review the settlement statement line by line before settlement. Small errors are corrected easily before funds clear; corrections after settlement are harder.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical net proceeds calculation</h2>
      <p>To work out what you will actually receive at settlement, run the calculation in this order:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Start with the expected sale price</li>
        <li>Subtract the mortgage payout amount</li>
        <li>Subtract the agent's commission, including GST</li>
        <li>Subtract vendor-paid advertising, including GST</li>
        <li>Subtract solicitor or conveyancer fees, including GST and disbursements</li>
        <li>Adjust for any council rates, water rates, or body corporate adjustments owed at settlement</li>
        <li>Subtract any other contractual deductions</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The result is your net proceeds. Always run this calculation before accepting a sale price; the price that looks acceptable on the contract may be tighter than expected once everything is properly accounted for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Do not assume agents are quoting GST-inclusive without confirming. The agency disclosure form usually states the GST treatment, but always check.</li>
        <li>Do not budget net proceeds based on the headline commission rate alone. Always work in inclusive numbers.</li>
        <li>Do not skip the line-by-line review of the settlement statement. The statement is your final opportunity to catch reconciliation errors before funds disburse.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>GST on commission is a real cost that meaningfully affects net proceeds, particularly at higher price points. Always work in GST-inclusive numbers when comparing agents, modelling outcomes, and budgeting the bottom line. Verify that the GST treatment is identical across all quotes before making the comparison. Run the full net proceeds calculation before accepting a sale price, and review the settlement statement line by line before funds clear.</p>

